7.1.1 - W11SR18: Ineffective SIAM Processes for Identity Lifecycle Management
ISM controls:
•	0411; 0418 (Relating to the identification of users and their access requirements).
•	0800; 1504 (Relating to the regular review of user access and privileges).
•	1173; 1401 (Relating to the management and protection of authentication credentials).
•	1649; 1650 (Relating to the timely revocation of access upon personnel changes).
Current Risk
A lack of effective Service Integration and Management (SIAM) processes and procedures, specifically regarding automated requests for the onboarding, offboarding, and access revalidation of agency staff within Ivanti Neurons, presents a security risk. This manual or fragmented approach may lead to unauthorised or misconfigured system and user access, potentially resulting in the compromise of the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of the agency’s system and its sensitive data.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MINOR	=	MEDIUM
Recommendations:
•	Automate Identity Lifecycle Management: Implement automated workflows within Ivanti Neurons that integrate with HR triggers to ensure user accounts are provisioned, modified, or decommissioned in real-time.
•	Enforce Regular Access Certification: Establish an automated, periodic revalidation process where managers must formally attest to the continued requirement of access for their staff.
•	Standardise RBAC within SIAM: Define and enforce clear Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) profiles to ensure that automated onboarding grants only the minimum necessary privileges by default.
- Treatment #1
•	Integrate the Ivanti Neurons platform with the primary Identity Provider (IdP) to ensure a "Single Source of Truth" for all user status changes.
•	Develop a formal "Offboarding Checklist" that is technically enforced to ensure all physical and logical access is revoked within 24 hours of personnel departure.
•	Establish a continuous monitoring dashboard to identify "orphan" accounts or accounts with stale access that have bypassed standard lifecycle processes.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
The transition from manual to automated identity lifecycle management significantly reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorised access due to administrative delays or errors. While the potential consequence remains "Minor," the likelihood of misconfigured or stale access leading to a security event is reduced to "Rare" through the implementation of rigorous, automated SIAM workflows.
